SIMPLE: wooden
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wooden
<hw>Wood"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Made or
consisting of wood; pertaining to, or resembling, wood; <as>as, a
<ex>wooden</ex> box; a <ex>wooden</ex> leg; a <ex>wooden</ex>
wedding</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Clumsy; awkward; ungainly; stiff;
spiritless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a bold man is out of countenance, he makes a very
<qex>wooden</qex> figure on it.</q> <rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His singing was, I confess, a little <qex>wooden</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>G. MacDonald.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wooden spoon</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Cambridge
University, Eng.)</fld> <cd>The last junior optime who takes a
university degree, -- denoting one who is only fit to stay at home and
stir porridge.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧We submit that a <xex>wooden spoon</xex> of
our day would not be justified in calling Galileo and Napier blockheads
because they never heard of the differential calculus.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Macaulay.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In some American colleges, the
lowest appointee of the junior year; sometimes, one especially popular
in his class, without reference to scholarship. Formerly, it was a
custom for classmates to present to this person a wooden spoon with
formal ceremonies.</cd> -- <col><b>Wooden ware</b></col>, <cd>a general
name for buckets, bowls, and other articles of domestic use, made of
wood.</cd> -- <col><b>Wooden wedding</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Wedding</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Woodenly</ent>⟦br⟧
